                        <msContents>
                            <summary>
                                <p>Stephens ascribes Tractatus de ideis and Replicacio de universalibus to Jan Hus, cf <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107330">Stephens (1847)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="35" to="39" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>. However Dziewicki (via previous research) argues convincingly that the first text is written by Wycliffe, while the other is by an unknown author, cf <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107538">Dziewicki (1902)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="liv" to="lxvi" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>. According to <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107544">Schieche (1979)</title>
                                    </bibl> there are 24 notes in Czech throughout the manuscript, found on: <locusGrp>
                                        <locus from="11v" to="11v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="14v" to="14v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="23r" to="23r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="29v" to="29v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="32r" to="32r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="40v" to="40v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="44v" to="44v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="52r" to="52r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="56r" to="56r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="58r" to="58r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="60r" to="60r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="64r" to="64r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="77v" to="77v" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="95r" to="95r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="96r" to="96r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="103r" to="103r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="117r" to="117r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="125r" to="125r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="127r" to="127r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="132r" to="132r" scheme="folios"/>
                                        <locus from="135r" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>
                                    </locusGrp>. The glosses are transcribed and translated into English in <bibl>
                                        <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107538">Dziewicki (1902)</title>
                                        <citedRange from="lxi" to="lxiii" unit="page"/>
                                    </bibl>.</p>
                            </summary>
                            <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="2r" to="34v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102764"> John Wycliffe </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Tractatus de individuacione temporis et instantis</title>
                                <incipit>CApitulum primum supponendo tempus esse declarat </incipit>
                                <explicit>quod peccat in spiritum sanctum subtrahendo ab eo oracionis suffragia</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit tractatus de indiuiduacione temporis et instantis quem composuit Subtilis vir magister Iohannes Wycleph</finalRubric>
                                <note>The treatise begins with a summary of the contents, the treatise proper begins on <locus from="2v" to="2v" scheme="folios"/> with: <quote>Intrando de tempore sunt aliqua ex dictis strictis capienda</quote>.</note>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="35r" to="53v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102764"> John Wycliffe </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Tractatus de ideis </title>
                                <incipit>INtrando <add place="above">tractando</add> de ydeis primo oportet querere si sint </incipit>
                                <explicit>quod omnis creatura et solum creatura habet ydeam propriam in deo</explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit tractatus de ydeis ergo laus domino </finalRubric>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="54r" to="77v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102764"> John Wycliffe </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Tractatus de materia et forma </title>
                                <incipit>CVm materia et forma sint vniuersalia mundi principalia restat de eis</incipit>
                                <explicit>et in vtroque primorum graduum nullum ens dicit presens uel aliquam essenciam preter deum </explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit tractatus de materia et forma Magistri Iohannes Vycleph O wicleff wycleff negednomu ty hlawu zwycless</finalRubric>
                                <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107538">Dziewicki (1902)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="163" to="242" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="78r" to="87r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Replicacio de universalibus </title>
                                <incipit>Presentem agrediendo replicacionis materiam in 3<hi rend="super">s</hi> partes distingo eam </incipit>
                                <explicit>quia lycet rex diuiditur in regem viuum et regem mortuum et depcitum et tamen nec rex viuus <add place="above">mortuus</add> nec depictus est rex </explicit>
                                <finalRubric>Explicit replicacio de vniversalibus quam si quis bene perspexerit videbit multo meliores raciones pro eisdem quam contra eadem prime enim ducere procedunt alie vero cum <del>o- --lis</del> et cetera </finalRubric>
                                <note>
                                    <locus from="87v" to="87v" scheme="folios"/>: blank.</note>
                                <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107538">Dziewicki (1902)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="129" to="161" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="88r" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <author>
                                    <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102764"> John Wycliffe </persName>
                                </author>
                                <title type="desc">Tractatus de universalibus</title>
                                <incipit>LIbellus de vniversalibus continet 15 capitula </incipit>
                                <explicit>Pono finem huic superficiali tractatui de vniversalibus ad alios tractatus de rebus prime intencionis ad quarum noticiam sentencia ista apparit agressurus</explicit>
                                <note>
                                    <locus from="88r" to="89v" scheme="folios"/>contain a summary of the treatise. The treatise proper starts on <locus from="89v" to="89v" scheme="folios"/> with: <quote>capitulum primum IN purgando erores de vniuersalibus et circa vniuersalia sunt 3a introductoria premouenda</quote>.</note>
                                <colophon>
                                    <locus from="135r" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>Explicit tractatus de veris vniuersalibus Magistri Venerabilis Iohannis Wycleph Sacre theologie veri et magni professoris Anno domini M<hi rend="super">o</hi> ccc<hi rend="super">o</hi> lxxxxviii in die Sancti Ieronimi Slawy per manus Hus de Hussynetz amen tak boh day</colophon>
                                <bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107547">Mueller (1985)</title>
                                </bibl>
                            </msItem>
                            <msItem>
                                <locus from="135v" to="136v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <title type="desc">Index</title>
                                <note>
                                    <p> Alphabetical index keyed to the medieval foliation.</p>
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="137r" to="147v" scheme="folios"/>: guidelines, but no text.</p>
                                </note>
                            </msItem>
                        </msContents>
                        <physDesc>
                            <objectDesc>
                                <supportDesc material="paper">
                                    <support>
                                        <p>
                                            <locus from="1" to="147" scheme="folios"/>
                                            <material>Paper</material>
                                            <dimensions type="leaf">
                                                <height quantity="220" unit="mm"/>
                                                <width quantity="150" unit="mm"/>
                                            </dimensions>
                                            <watermark n="1">
                                                <locusGrp>
                                                    <locus from="2" to="147" scheme="folios"/>
                                                </locusGrp>
                                                <term type="watermarkMotif">Unidentified motif (possibly two versions).</term>
                                                <note>Possibly a tower with three notches. Somewhat similar to Piccard III, II, 1-41.</note>
                                            </watermark>
                                        </p>
                                    </support>
                                    <extent>
                                        <measure type="textblockLeaves" quantity="147" unit="folios"/>
                                    </extent>
                                    <foliation>
                                        <locus from="2r" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>: medieval foliation in arabic numeral in red ink, 1-134. N.B. Many of the titles in the bibliography refers to the medieval foliation rather than the modern. </foliation>
                                    <condition>Leaves affected by damp stains in many places, e.g. <locus from="26" to="28" scheme="folios"/>.</condition>
                                </supportDesc>
                                <layoutDesc>
                                    <layout columns="1" writtenLines="35 38">
